    Over the past ten years I‚Äôve made ten different versions of my website. I call it my annual portfolio ‚Äúrefresh‚Äù since the content usually stays the same. I do always start with a blank CSS file.

  figure
    img.wide(src='/assets/images/thoughts/lynnandtonic-version-old.jpg', width='1200', height='821', alt='four browser windows with four different sites')
    figcaption.footnote some past iterations of #[a(href='https://lynnandtonic.com') lynnandtonic.com]

  :markdown-it
    I do this each year for a few reasons:

    - to ensure I‚Äôll complete at least one non-work project
    - to experiment with and learn new techniques (a few standout refreshes were my first attempts at responsive design, flexbox, and this year, CSS grid)
    - a year is about the right amount of time for a version to exist where I don‚Äôt feel sad once I sit down to change it

    Also, a truly great thing about redoing my own site is that it‚Äôs fully mine and I can do whatever the heck I want. üòä

    A very small percentage of my portfolio‚Äôs visitors are [airport enthusiasts](https://airportcod.es/), [Top Chef viewers](https://topchefstats.com/), and family (hi, mom). But the primary audience is overwhelmingly web designers, developers, and tech recruiters. These are people who know how websites are built and might take an extra minute to inspect things. I wanted to design around that.

    ## Concept and inspiration

    For years we‚Äôve been telling the world that a website doesn‚Äôt need to look the exact same in every browser for every user. With responsive design and progressive enhancement, users *will* see things differently. Not everyone needs to experience the entirety of the site.

    But could I make people *want* to experience all of it? Could I surprise them by taking these concepts to an absurd extreme?

    I love to resize my browser and see how the layout responds and how the designer decided when things change and what gets dropped or added. I know lots of other people do this too. I initially thought I could subvert expectations by making the ubiquitous phone, tablet, and desktop breakpoints trigger completely different layouts with unique styles, colors, and type treatments. Three sites in one.

    The changes, as dramatic as they might have been, still felt too conventional. You already expect something to happen at tablet size and then again for phones.

    I‚Äôd recently watched a [YouTube video](https://youtu.be/Vy2Vhnqtu8I) about the [Kuleshov Effect](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kuleshov_effect), a term in film editing that describes ‚Äúa phenomenon by which viewers derive more meaning from the interaction of two sequential shots than from a single shot in isolation.‚Äù A metaphorical bell chimed in my head.

    There‚Äôs preexisting meaning for a site to have three (or a few more) distinct layouts: supporting common devices. But what would it *mean* for there to be 10, 15, or ultimately 21 distinct designs that ‚Äúsit‚Äù side by side for you to discover one at a time, one after the other. Each one may be unremarkable on its own, but it‚Äôs the relationships (and differences) with the ones to the left/right and to the 18 others that make each one worth looking at.

